#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:6
msgid ""
"The `Cursor` and `AsyncCursor` classes are the main objects to send commands "
"to a PostgreSQL database session. They are normally created by the "
"connection's `~Connection.cursor()` method."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:10
msgid ""
"Using the `!name` parameter on `!cursor()` will create a `ServerCursor` or "
"`AsyncServerCursor`, which can be used to retrieve partial results from a "
"database."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:14
msgid ""
"Other cursor classes can be created by directly instantiating them, or can "
"be set as `Connection.cursor_factory` to require them on `!cursor()` call."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:17
msgid ""
"This page describe the details of the `!Cursor` class interface. Please "
"refer to :ref:`cursor-types` for general information about the different "
"types of cursors available in Psycopg."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:23
msgid "The `!Cursor` class"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:27
msgid ""
"This class implements a `DBAPI-compliant interface`__. It is what the "
"classic `Connection.cursor()` method returns. `AsyncConnection.cursor()` "
"will create instead `AsyncCursor` objects, which have the same set of method "
"but expose an `asyncio` interface and require `!async` and `!await` keywords "
"to operate."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:37
msgid ""
"Cursors behave as context managers: on block exit they are closed and "
"further operation will not be possible. Closing a cursor will not terminate "
"a transaction or a session though."
msgstr ""

