#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:335
msgid ""
"An helper object used to convert queries and parameters before sending them "
"to PostgreSQL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:339
msgid ""
"This attribute is exposed because it might be helpful to debug problems when "
"the communication between Python and PostgreSQL doesn't work as expected. "
"For this reason, the attribute is available when a query fails too."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:345
msgid ""
"You shouldn't consider it part of the public interface of the object: it "
"might change without warnings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:348
msgid "Except this warning, I guess."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:350
msgid ""
"If you would like to build reliable features using this object, please get "
"in touch so we can try and design an useful interface for it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:354
msgid "Among the properties currently exposed by this object:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:356
msgid ""
"`!query` (`!bytes`): the query effectively sent to PostgreSQL. It will have "
"Python placeholders (``%s``\\-style) replaced with PostgreSQL ones (``$1``, "
"``$2``\\-style)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:360
msgid ""
"`!params` (sequence of `!bytes`): the parameters passed to PostgreSQL, "
"adapted to the database format."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:363
msgid ""
"`!types` (sequence of `!int`): the OID of the parameters passed to "
"PostgreSQL."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:366
msgid ""
"`!formats` (sequence of `pq.Format`): whether the parameter format is text "
"or binary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:371
msgid "The `!ClientCursor` class"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:373
msgid "See :ref:`client-side-binding-cursors` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:377
msgid ""
"This `Cursor` subclass has exactly the same interface of its parent class, "
"but, instead of sending query and parameters separately to the server, it "
"merges them on the client and sends them as a non-parametric query on the "
"server. This allows, for instance, to execute parametrized data definition "
"statements and other :ref:`problematic queries <server-side-binding>`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/client_cursor.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.client_cursor.ClientCursorMixin.mogrify:1
msgid "Return the query and parameters merged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/client_cursor.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.client_cursor.ClientCursorMixin.mogrify:3
msgid ""
"Parameters are adapted and merged to the query the same way that `!"
"execute()` would do."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:389
msgid "The parameters to pass to the query, if any."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:394
msgid "The `!ServerCursor` class"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:396
msgid "See :ref:`server-side-cursors` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:400
msgid ""
"This class also implements a `DBAPI-compliant interface`__. It is created by "
"`Connection.cursor()` specifying the `!name` parameter. Using this object "
"results in the creation of an equivalent PostgreSQL cursor in the server. "
"DBAPI-extension methods (such as `~Cursor.copy()` or `~Cursor.stream()`) are "
"not implemented on this object: use a normal `Cursor` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:409
msgid ""
"Most attribute and methods behave exactly like in `Cursor`, here are "
"documented the differences:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.ServerCursor.name:1
msgid "The name of the cursor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.ServerCursor.scrollable:1
msgid "Whether the cursor is scrollable or not."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.ServerCursor.scrollable:3
msgid ""
"If `!None` leave the choice to the server. Use `!True` if you want to use "
"`scroll()` on the cursor."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:415
msgid ""
"The PostgreSQL DECLARE_ statement documentation for the description of :sql:"
"`[NO] SCROLL`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/__init__.py:docstring
#: of psycopg.ServerCursor.withhold:1
msgid "If the cursor can be used after the creating transaction has committed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:420
msgid ""
"The PostgreSQL DECLARE_ statement documentation for the description of :sql:"
"`{WITH|WITHOUT} HOLD`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:428
msgid ""
"Closing a server-side cursor is more important than closing a client-side "
"one because it also releases the resources on the server, which otherwise "
"might remain allocated until the end of the session (memory, locks). Using "
"the pattern::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:433
msgid ""
"with conn.cursor():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:436
msgid ""
"is especially useful so that the cursor is closed at the end of the block."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/_server_cursor.py:docstring
#: of psycopg._server_cursor.ServerCursor.execute:1
#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/_server_cursor_async.py:docstring
#: psycopg._server_cursor_async.AsyncServerCursor.execute:1
msgid "Open a cursor to execute a query to the database."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:451
msgid "Create a server cursor with given `!name` and the `!query` in argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:453
msgid ""
"If using :sql:`DECLARE` is not appropriate (for instance because the cursor "
"is returned by calling a stored procedure) you can avoid to use `!"
"execute()`, crete the cursor in other ways, and use directly the `!fetch*()` "
"methods instead. See :ref:`cursor-steal` for an example."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:458
msgid ""
"Using `!execute()` more than once will close the previous cursor and open a "
"new one with the same name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/_server_cursor.py:docstring
#: of psycopg._server_cursor.ServerCursor.executemany:1
#: ../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.14/site-packages/psycopg/_server_cursor_async.py:docstring
#: psycopg._server_cursor_async.AsyncServerCursor.executemany:1
msgid "Method not implemented for server-side cursors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:466
msgid ""
"These methods use the FETCH_ SQL statement to retrieve some of the records "
"from the cursor's current position."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:473
msgid ""
"You can also iterate on the cursor to read its result one at time with::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:476
msgid ""
"for record in cur:\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:479
msgid ""
"In this case, the records are not fetched one at time from the server but "
"they are retrieved in batches of `itersize` to reduce the number of server "
"roundtrips."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:485
msgid ""
"Number of records to fetch at time when iterating on the cursor. The default "
"is 100."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:490
msgid ""
"This method uses the MOVE_ SQL statement to move the current position in the "
"server-side cursor, which will affect following `!fetch*()` operations. If "
"you need to scroll backwards you should probably call `~Connection.cursor()` "
"using `scrollable=True`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:495
msgid ""
"Note that PostgreSQL doesn't provide a reliable way to report when a cursor "
"moves out of bound, so the method might not raise `!IndexError` when it "
"happens, but it might rather stop at the cursor boundary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:503
msgid "The `!RawCursor` and `!RawServerCursor` class"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:505
msgid "See :ref:`raw-query-cursors` for details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:509
msgid ""
"This `Cursor` subclass has the same interface of the parent class but "
"supports placeholders in PostgreSQL format (``$1``, ``$2``...) rather than "
"in Python format (``%s``). Only positional parameters are supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:518
msgid ""
"This `ServerCursor` subclass has the same interface of the parent class but "
"supports placeholders in PostgreSQL format (``$1``, ``$2``...) rather than "
"in Python format (``%s``). Only positional parameters are supported."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:527
msgid "Async cursor classes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:529
msgid ""
"Every `Cursor` class has an equivalent `!Async` version exposing the same "
"semantic with an `!async` interface. The main interface is described in "
"`AsyncCursor`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:536
msgid ""
"This class implements a DBAPI-inspired interface, with all the blocking "
"methods implemented as coroutines. Unless specified otherwise, non-blocking "
"methods are shared with the `Cursor` class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:540
msgid ""
"The following methods have the same behaviour of the matching `!Cursor` "
"methods, but should be called using the `await` keyword."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:552
msgid ""
"async with conn.cursor():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:555
msgid "to close the cursor automatically when the block is exited."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:565
msgid ""
"async with cursor.copy() as copy:\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:574
msgid ""
"async for record in cursor.stream(query):\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:586
msgid "You can also use::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:588
msgid ""
"async for record in cursor:\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:591
msgid "to iterate on the async cursor results."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:597
msgid ""
"This class is the `!async` equivalent of `ClientCursor`. The differences w.r."
"t. the sync counterpart are the same described in `AsyncCursor`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:606
msgid ""
"This class implements a DBAPI-inspired interface as the `AsyncCursor` does, "
"but wraps a server-side cursor like the `ServerCursor` class. It is created "
"by `AsyncConnection.cursor()` specifying the `!name` parameter."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:610
msgid ""
"The following are the methods exposing a different (async) interface from "
"the `ServerCursor` counterpart, but sharing the same semantics."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:616
msgid "You can close the cursor automatically using::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:618
msgid ""
"async with conn.cursor(\"name\") as cursor:\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:629
msgid "You can also iterate on the cursor using::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:631
msgid ""
"async for record in cur:\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:639
msgid ""
"This class is the `!async` equivalent of `RawCursor`. The differences w.r.t. "
"the sync counterpart are the same described in `AsyncCursor`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../api/cursors.rst:647
msgid ""
"This class is the `!async` equivalent of `RawServerCursor`. The differences "
"w.r.t. the sync counterpart are the same described in `AsyncServerCursor`."
msgstr ""
